Well-grown chicks in a nest in a brazil coral tree beside a creek. This is a favoured nest site; I've seen White Ibis nesting here in previous years.

Three ibis dropping in to check out a suburban back yard that was recently (last year) stripped of every last tree shrub etc and laid with turf...Not so good for the possums, kookaburras, peewees and other critters that used to live there.. but good luck for the Ibis.
bin chicken excursion

Seen all by itself - no others of this species anywhere near - in Blackwood Rd, Geebung, morning of 26th September 2020.
White Ibis atop a large brazil coral tree in centre secton of 7th Brigade Park, Chermside. In previous years they have nested in this location.

Small breeding colony established in the canopy of large brazil coral tree in a bend of Downfall Creek within centre section of 7th Brigade Park, Chermside.  Note the presence of young chicks.  I have included a panned-back image of the location (photographed from the southwest, looking northeast along the creek).
Frequently seen foraging in this location.
One individual, foraging in a concrete gutter - which is all there is of "Downfall Creek" where it passes through "Melaleuca Green" in Chermside West.  A dreadfully degraded environment.
Three birds; foraging near a fig tree, in company with two buff-banded rails.
Seen on a house-roof.
Only one.

Foraging in a wet low-lying area, along with swamp hens and a currawong.  In previous years in this sort of weather I've seen buff-banded rails and black ducks in this area, but there were none there on 2/7/21 - only the Ibis, swamphens and currawong.
This bird seems to be sitting already on a nest, on the top of a big old coral tree beside Downfall Creek.
Small breeding colony; group of birds with nests constructed in a large brazil coral tree on creek flats.
Often seen hanging about in this area.
Just one.  Cruising about in the vicinity of the main entrance of Royal Brisbane Hospital.
Just one. Foraging along the slope in the lower/ eastern section of Rainbow Lorikeet Park, Aspley: in badly degraded and devegetated "channelised" creek-line.
Making use of a fountain in Queen St Mall, Brisbane City.
One bird. In a small 'pocket park' that doesn't support much wildlife.
A burst or leaking pipe has created an ersatz paperbark swamp; the White Ibis have moved right in and are taking advantage.
Found in parking lot.
Keeping company with cormorants and a black duck.
A couple of crested pigeons there as well but I'm posting this as an Ibis sighting.

Several birds. I think they are preparing to nest; they have nested before as a small colony (about a dozen) in coral trees in this location, at a bend in the creek.  This area seems to be a preferred nest site.
Keeping company with dusky moorhens in a little pond.

One of the few signs of life in a truly dismal piece of 'landscaping' of so-called public 'greenspace' (sic).  Here Downfall Creek has been reduced to a hot and bare concrete gutter and the riparian vegetation consists of exotic lawn grasses and weeds, various, and a strip of trees (along top  of bank) with little or no understorey.
Just one, in a desolate strip of despised, denuded and degraded creek-line.
Just one bird. Hangs around this area.
Two birds.

Somehow finding something to eat in a location where all in-stream and on-bank vegetation whether native or non-native was sprayed with a heavy dose of glyphosate or similar, several months ago, and has turned to grey dust.
There were several birds, in and near a small pool.

Not sure what even an ibis could be finding to eat here... an entire section of creekline has had all or most in-channel and on-bank vegetation of any kind poisoned so thoroughly with glyphosate that there has been nothing alive for months.
Just one, hanging around on the footpath.
Two birds.  Final shot is panned back to show habitat; birds are visible in far distance in the drain/ gutter next to a few pine trees.
